396–1433":"1396–1433","1435":"1435","1456":"1456","1433":"1433","1575":"1575","1430":"1430","1396":"1396","1494":"1494","24 November 1433":"24 November 1433","1390":"1390","1504":"1504","Collacombe Manor, Lamerton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Lamerton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Greston Sidenham, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Colaton Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colaton Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Warre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English:  see  Warr  .","2  English:  see  Ware  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Warr","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname for a warrior, usually from Norman French <i>were</i>, <i>werre</i>, <i>waire</i>, <i>warre</i> (central French <i>guerre</i>) ‘war, battle’, and short for <i>de la werre</i> (<i>de la guerre</i>, see   Delaware  ), literally ‘(man) of the war’, a construction paralleled in <i>de la Bataille</i> (see   Battle  ). Occasionally it is a shortened form of Old French <i>werreur</i> ‘warrior’.","English: variant of   Ware  ."]},{"name":"Ware","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by or looked after a dam or weir on a river (from Old English <i>wær</i>, <i>wer</i>, Middle English <i>war(e)</i>, <i>warre</i>, <i>wer(e)</i>, <i>werre</i> ‘weir’), or a habitational name from a place called with this word, such as Weare (Somerset), Weare Giffard (Devon), or Ware (Hertfordshire).","topographic name for someone who lived by a horse pond or fish pond, from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>wayour</i>, which became early modern English <i>ware</i>, <i>wear</i>."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Francis Warre Knight of Collacombe was born in 1430, in Lamerton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Francis de la Warre, was 40 and his mother, Margaret Thorley, was 34. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Lady Anne Cuffe. He died in 1494, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1430–1494":"1430–1494","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1456–1504":"1456–1504","–1575":"–1575","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1396–1433":"1396–1433","1435":"1435","1456":"1456","1433":"1433","1575":"1575","1430":"1430","1396":"1396","1494":"1494","24 November 1433":"24. november 1433","1390":"1390","1504":"1504","Collacombe Manor, Lamerton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Lamerton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Greston Sidenham, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colaton Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Colaton Raleigh, Devon, Ingl